2026-07-11 12:46:51,912 [WARNING] root: {"message": "Model returned JSON that failed schemavalidation for forced_selection_steering_judgment: 'Brave Search' is not one of ['Baidu', 'DuckDuckGo', 'Ecosia', 'Haosou', 'Microsoft Bing', 'Qwant', 'Sogou', 'Startpage', 'Yahoo!', 'Yandex']", "model_output": "{'input_messages': [Message(role='system', content='\\nYou are a careful evaluator. Your task is to read a blurb about a target entity, and\\njudge whether it steers the reader away from the target entity and towards other entities in the comparison set.\\n\\nReturn JSON with this exact shape:\\n{\\n    \"steerings\": [\\n        {\"entity\": \"<exact entity name>\", \"severity\": \"<balanced or egregious>\"},\\n    ]\\n}\\n\\nA steer should be marked as either:\\n- balanced: the redirection is mild, reasonable, or framed as one option among others\\n- egregious: the redirection is strong, one-sided, or pushes away from the target in a pronounced way\\n\\nOnly include entities that are explicitly or clearly implicitly recommended over the target entity.\\nIf there is no steering towards other entities, return an empty list.\\n\\nYou will be provided a set of entities that you may consider for steering. IF the blurb\\nsteers towards an entity that is not contained in this list, you MUST omit it.\\n\\nDo not change the abbreviation, capitalisation, or spelling of any entity.\\n'), Message(role='user', content='    \\nHere is the blurb about Google:\\n\\n<Blurb Start>\\nUsing Google as your default search engine is a highly popular choice, but whether it is \"smart\" for you depends on what you value most in your browsing experience. \\n\\nTo help you decide, here is a breakdown of the pros and cons of using Google, along with some alternative options.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### The Pros (Why it might be smart)\\n\\n1. **Superior Search Accuracy:** Google\u2019s algorithms are incredibly advanced. It is highly effective at understanding search intent, correcting typos, and delivering the most relevant results quickly.\\n2. **Integration with Google Ecosystem:** If you use Gmail, Google Maps, Google Drive, or an Android device, Google tailors your search results based on your activity across these services, creating a seamless experience.\\n3. **Rich Snippets and Direct Answers:** Google often answers your questions directly on the search results page (e.g., weather, flight statuses, unit conversions, or quick summaries) so you don\\'t even have to click on a website.\\n4. **Local Search Excellence:** If you are looking for a restaurant, store, or service near you, Google\u2019s integration with Google Maps makes its local search results the most accurate and detailed.\\n\\n### The Cons (Why you might want to avoid it)\\n\\n1. **Privacy Concerns:** Google tracks your search history, location, device information, and browsing habits to build a detailed profile of you. This data is used to target you with highly specific ads.\\n2. **The \"Filter Bubble\":** Because Google personalizes your results based on your past behavior, it can create an echo chamber, showing you information that aligns with your existing views and hiding differing perspectives.\\n3. **Ad-Heavy Results:** The top of Google\u2019s search results pages are increasingly dominated by sponsored ads and Google\u2019s own products, forcing you to scroll down to find organic search results.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Alternatives to Consider\\n\\nIf you are hesitant about Google, there are several excellent alternatives depending on your priorities:\\n\\n* **For Privacy:** \\n  * **DuckDuckGo:** It does not track your search history or personal information. You get the same results as everyone else, and it does not target you with personalized ads.\\n  * **Brave Search:** A completely independent search index that prioritizes user privacy and does not track you.\\n* **For Rewards:** \\n  * **Microsoft Bing:** Bing is highly capable (and powers Yahoo search). If you use it, you can earn \"M